Rx, version 1.0, is now available.

Copies can be obtained by ftp from prep.ai.mit.edu:pub/gnu/rx-1.0.tar.gz
and from other sites (see the list of mirror sites at the end of this
message).

Rx is an implementation of the standard regular expression matching
functions specified by POSIX.2 (and then some).

The distribution now includes a texinfo manual.

The largest change in this version of Rx is an algorithmic improvement
based on advice form Henry Spencer.  The resulting matcher is often a
little slower than older versions of Rx, but more importantly, where
older versions of Rx used unreasonable amounts of time or space, the
new version gives reasonable performance.

Older versions of Rx included implementations of the standard GNU
regexp entry points, as well as of the traditional BSD entry points.
In the interest of saving time, these have not been ported to Rx 1.0,
though contributions of implementations are welcome.

Please report bugs to bug-gnu-utils@prep.ai.mit.edu.

